## 3. Common Layouts and Their Trade-offs

### 3.1 Cell-centered grids

Start simply: put each photo with its geometric center in the middle of a uniform cell. This is the most straightforward grid layout — the photo's center is aligned inside the cell.

Photos come in many shapes and proportions. Place every photo centered in identical cells and you get inconsistent empty space: portraits tend to leave bars on the left and right, landscapes on the top and bottom. The empty space doesn't align across the grid, which breaks the rhythm.

![Contain/fit approach in a square grid](./assets/square-grid-fit.svg "Photos fitted (not cropped) into square cells — the square photo dominates while others shrink")

A common baseline is `object-fit: contain`. It shows the full image inside the cell (no cropping); the trade-off is the inconsistent letterboxing described above.

Example (no-crop, `contain`):

```css
.gallery {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(200px, 1fr));
  gap: 0.5rem;
}

.gallery img {
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  object-fit: contain;
}
```

 

That inconsistent empty space is the reason many galleries crop previews: a fixed target ratio (square, 4:5, etc.) keeps cell dimensions uniform and the page visually consistent. Below is the more common strategy: crop everything to a fixed aspect ratio so every cell looks identical. The typical CSS for that approach is:

```css
.gallery {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(200px, 1fr));
  gap: 0.5rem;
}

.gallery img {
  aspect-ratio: 1 / 1; /* or 4/5, 3/2, etc. */
  object-fit: cover;
}
```

![Square grid illustration](./assets/square-grid.svg "Fixed aspect ratio grid — all photos cropped to squares")

This approach gives you maximum space efficiency and a strong visual rhythm. Because every cell shares the same dimensions, gaps align into continuous leading lines: vertical edges stack into vertical guides that repeat across rows, and horizontal edges stack into horizontal guides that repeat across columns. That alignment is what we mean by rhythm — consistent spacing and repeated edges that guide the eye.

Compare this to the `contain` baseline above: letterboxing breaks those lines and the grid feels inconsistent. The fixed-aspect grid can produce a strong sense of order, but with high contrast and thick gaps it can generate the [Hermann grid illusion](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grid_illusion) — phantom dark spots at intersections of white gaps that make the layout feel mechanical rather than organic.

![Contain/fit grid with broken leading lines](./assets/square-grid-fit-leading-lines.svg "Fitted photos break the leading lines — gaps become inconsistent")

With `contain`, images retain their entire composition, but the letterboxing breaks leading lines across the grid; `cover` preserves the visual rhythm by aligning cell content but crops image edges.

**Center crop** is the naive default, but it often cuts subjects positioned using rule-of-thirds. **Smart crop** libraries like [smartcrop.js](https://github.com/jwagner/smartcrop.js) do better — they analyze edges, skin tones, and visual weight using computationally cheap heuristics (no AI required). **AI-assisted crop** services like Cloudinary go further by detecting subjects and faces — more accurate, but requires server-side processing. **Editorial tight crop** is a different strategy entirely: an artistic choice where previews crop dramatically tighter than the full image, creating intrigue.

In short: one option preserves every photo (`contain`) but introduces inconsistent empty space and broken leading lines; the other (`cover`) makes the grid tidy at the cost of cropping image content. If you want equal visual weight between orientations without cropping, the next section describes an alternative approach.

#### The Aspect Ratio Change Problem

But here's something worse than choosing how to crop: changing your mind later. Once you pick a fixed aspect ratio, you're stuck with it. Why? Because changing it breaks all your existing content.

Instagram learned this the hard way. They originally enforced square previews — a neutral choice that worked on both mobile and desktop. In early 2025, they shifted to portrait-oriented rectangles, which makes sense for a mobile-first platform.

But the change was destructive. Photos that were composed for square display suddenly got cropped differently. Subjects intentionally placed at edges — perfectly visible in the old square previews — were now cut off.

![Instagram — original square previews](https://share.kadykov.com/images/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout/instagram-square.avif "Instagram's original square grid")

![Instagram — newer rectangular previews](https://share.kadykov.com/images/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout/instagram-rectangular.avif "Portrait-oriented previews — edge content gets cropped")

The lesson: fixed aspect ratios require commitment. Changing them later harms content that was composed for the original ratio.

