### 3.2 Column Layouts (Pinterest, Unsplash)

Okay, so forcing everything into one aspect ratio requires cropping. What if we don't want to crop? The next simplest option is column layouts: fixed column widths, variable heights. Photos keep their original aspect ratio — nothing gets cut off.

```css
.gallery {
  columns: 3;
  column-gap: 1rem;
}

.gallery img {
  width: 100%;
  margin-bottom: 1rem;
}
```

![Column-based layout](./assets/columns.svg "Column layout — portrait photos dominate visually")

This sounds great — we're preserving aspect ratios and maximizing space usage. But there's a problem: **portrait photos dominate**. They're taller, so they occupy more visual area and naturally draw more attention. A single portrait shot can tower over two landscape photos stacked vertically.

![Unsplash — column layout](https://share.kadykov.com/images/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout/unsplash-columns.avif "Unsplash's column layout — portrait shots visually dominate")

Plus, captions under variable-height images create uneven spacing, which looks messy.

#### Rhythm: Horizontal Only (Monotonous Vertical Stripes)

What about visual rhythm? Columns have equal widths, so the vertical gaps between them align perfectly — forming strong **vertical leading lines**. These vertical lines repeat horizontally, creating **horizontal rhythm**.

But photos have different heights, so horizontal gaps between photos occur at different vertical positions in each column. These gaps don't align across columns — no horizontal leading lines form, so there's **no vertical rhythm**.

![Column layout with leading lines](./assets/columns-leading-lines.svg "Vertical leading lines are strong — horizontal gaps are scattered, forming no lines")

The result: monotonous vertical stripes. The eye moves smoothly left-to-right (horizontal rhythm), but scanning top-to-bottom feels structureless.

#### The Fill Order Problem

Columns preserve aspect ratios and feel less rigid than fixed grids, but they introduce a new problem: fill order. CSS multi-column fills top-to-bottom, then moves to the next column — inherited from text layout.

![CSS column fill order](./assets/columns-CSS-order.svg "Pure CSS: 1-2 in first column, 3-4 in second, 5-6 in third")

With longer galleries, this becomes problematic. Recent photos (which users want to see first) end up at the bottom of the first column — below the fold:

![CSS column order with long gallery](./assets/columns-CSS-order-long.svg "With 10 photos, the first row shows 1, 5, 9 — photos 2, 3, 4 are hidden below")

Real implementations use JavaScript to place images left-to-right:

![Natural fill order](./assets/columns-natural-order.svg "JavaScript-controlled order: row by row, left to right")

